    Let <fr:tex>W</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>F</fr:tex>, and <fr:tex>\bar {F}</fr:tex> be three finite opposite filtrations, and <fr:tex>\sigma </fr:tex> a sequence <fr:tex>(p_i,q_i)_{i\geqslant 0}</fr:tex> pairs of integers satisfying

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;a. &quot;">
        <fr:tex>p_i\leqslant  p_j</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>q_i\leqslant  q_j</fr:tex> for <fr:tex>i\geqslant  j</fr:tex>, and
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;b. &quot;">
        <fr:tex>p_i+q_i=p_0+q_0-i+1</fr:tex> for <fr:tex>i&gt;0</fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol>


    Set <fr:tex>p=p_0</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>q=q_0</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>n=-p-q</fr:tex>, and
    <fr:tex
display="block">       A_\sigma        = \left ( \sum _{0\leqslant  i}(W^{n+i}(A)\cap  F^{p_i}(A)) \right )       \cap  \left ( \sum _{0\leqslant  i}(W^{n+i}(A)\cap \bar {F}^{q_i}(A)) \right ).     </fr:tex>
    Then the projection from <fr:tex>W^n(A)</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr}_W^n(A)</fr:tex> induces an isomorphism
    <fr:tex
display="block">       A_\sigma        \xrightarrow {\sim } A^{p,q} \subset  \operatorname {Gr}_W^n(A).     </fr:tex></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree
