    <fr:p>
      We will prove by induction on <fr:tex>k</fr:tex> the following claim:
    </fr:p>

    <fr:p><fr:em>
        The projection from <fr:tex>W^n(A)/W^{n+k}</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr}_W^n(A)</fr:tex> induces an isomorphism from
        <fr:tex
display="block">           \begin {aligned}             \Bigg [             &amp;\left ( \sum _{i&lt;k} (W^{n+i}(A)\cap  F^{p_i}(A)) + W^{n+k}(A) \right )           \\\cap              &amp;\left ( \sum _{i&lt;k} (W^{n+i}(A)\cap \bar {F}^{q_i}(A)) + W^{n+k}(A) \right )             \Bigg ] / W^{n+k}(A)           \end {aligned}           \tag{$*_k$}         </fr:tex>
        to <fr:tex>A^{p,q}\subset \operatorname {Gr}_W^n(A)</fr:tex>.
      </fr:em></fr:p>

    <fr:p>
      For <fr:tex>k=1</fr:tex>, this is exactly the definition of <fr:tex>A^{p,q}</fr:tex>.
    </fr:p>

    <fr:p>
      By (i) of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.5"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.5.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="1.2.5"></fr:ref> we have

      <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>677</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-ii-1.2.8.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.2.8.1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>1.2.8.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.2.8</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block">           F^{p_k}(\operatorname {Gr}_W^{n+k}(A)) \oplus  \bar {F}^{q_k}(\operatorname {Gr}_W^{n+k}(A))           \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {Gr}_W^{n+k}(A).         \tag{1.2.8.1}         </fr:tex></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
      Set
      <fr:tex
display="block">         \begin {aligned}           B &amp;= \sum _{i&lt;k} (W^{n+i}(A)\cap  F^{p_i}(A))         \\C &amp;= \sum _{i&lt;k} (W^{n+i}(A)\cap \bar {F}^{q_i}(A))         \\B' &amp;= (W^{n+k}(A)\cap  F^{p_k}(A)) + W^{n+k+1}(A)         \\C' &amp;= (W^{n+k}(A)\cap \bar {F}^{q_k}(A)) + W^{n+k+1}(A)         \\D &amp;= W^{n+k}(A)         \\E &amp;= W^{n+k+1}(A).         \end {aligned}       </fr:tex></fr:p>

    <fr:p><fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.8.1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.8.1.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="1.2.8.1"></fr:ref> can then be written as
      <fr:tex
display="block">         \begin {aligned}           B'+C' &amp;= D         \\B'\cap  C' &amp;= E.         \end {aligned}       </fr:tex>
      We also have, since <fr:tex>p_k\leqslant  p_i</fr:tex> (for <fr:tex>i\leqslant  k</fr:tex>),
      <fr:tex
display="block">         B\cap  D         \subset  F^{p_k}(A) \cap  W^{n+k}(A)         \subset  B'       </fr:tex>
      and, since <fr:tex>q_k\leqslant  q_i</fr:tex> (for <fr:tex>i\leqslant  k</fr:tex>),
      <fr:tex
display="block">         C\cap  D         \subset  \bar {F}^{q_k}(A)\cap  W^{n+k}(A)         \subset  C'.       </fr:tex></fr:p>

    <fr:p>
      The claim (<fr:tex>*_{k+1}</fr:tex>) and then follows from (<fr:tex>*_k</fr:tex>) and the following lemma.
    </fr:p>
